    cellular: { title: "Pathophysiology of Lemierre Syndrome", content: "Lemierre syndrome is a potentially fatal condition involving septic thrombophlebitis of the internal jugular vein (IJV) following oropharyngeal infection, most commonly caused by the anaerobic gram-negative bacterium Fusobacterium necrophorum. The pathogenesis begins with pharyngitis or peritonsillar abscess, with bacterial invasion of the parapharyngeal space and lateral pharyngeal vein, extending to the internal jugular vein where infection causes endothelial damage, platelet activation, and formation of infected thrombus. Septic emboli from the IJV thrombus disseminate hematogenously, most commonly to the lungs (causing cavitary lesions, empyema, and septic pulmonary emboli), but also to joints, liver, and soft tissues. The clinical presentation includes persistent sore throat, high spiking fevers with rigors, unilateral neck swelling and tenderness along the sternocleidomastoid, and pleuritic chest pain from pulmonary emboli. The RN monitors vital signs, assesses neck for swelling and tenderness, monitors respiratory status for septic pulmonary emboli, administers prolonged IV antibiotic therapy (beta-lactam plus metronidazole or monotherapy with a carbapenem), monitors for complications including septic shock and DIC, and assists with interventional radiology or surgical drainage of IJV if required." },
