    cellular: { title: "Pathophysiology of Lithium Toxicity", content: "Lithium, a monovalent cation used as a mood stabilizer for bipolar disorder, has a narrow therapeutic index (therapeutic serum level 0.6-1.2 mEq/L) and is eliminated almost entirely by renal excretion. Lithium is freely filtered at the glomerulus and 80% is reabsorbed in the proximal tubule via sodium channels -- any condition that enhances proximal tubular sodium reabsorption (dehydration, sodium depletion, NSAIDs reducing renal blood flow, ACE inhibitors, thiazide diuretics) proportionally increases lithium reabsorption and raises serum levels. Toxicity affects multiple organ systems: neurological (tremor, ataxia, dysarthria, confusion, seizures, coma), gastrointestinal (nausea, vomiting, diarrhea), renal (nephrogenic diabetes insipidus from downregulation of aquaporin-2 channels, chronic tubulointerstitial nephropathy), cardiac (T-wave flattening, sinus node dysfunction, QT prolongation), and endocrine (hypothyroidism from inhibition of thyroid hormone synthesis and release). The RN monitors serum lithium levels (drawn 12 hours post-dose), monitors renal function and thyroid function regularly, maintains adequate hydration and sodium intake, recognizes early toxicity signs (coarse tremor, GI symptoms), administers IV normal saline for volume repletion, assists with hemodialysis for severe toxicity (level greater than 4 mEq/L or severe symptoms), and educates patients about drug interactions and conditions that alter lithium clearance." },
